            Hint
**********************************************-->


<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<ul>
  <conditionalContent>
    <case condition="$oneSol">
  <li>There is one solution, because the factor <math simplify="numberspreserveorder">(x - $s)</math> occurs twice in the final factored form. This is known as a <em>repeated root</em>. You should graph this to see what it looks like!
    <md>
      <mrow>$generalForm = 0</mrow>
      <mrow>$factoredForm = 0</mrow>
      <mrow>x = $s</mrow>
    </md></li>      
    </case>
    <case condition="$twoSol">
  <li>There are two solutions, because the final factored form has two distinct roots. You should graph this to see what it looks like!
    <md>
      <mrow>$generalForm = 0</mrow>
      <mrow>$factoredForm = 0</mrow>
      <mrow>x = $s\;\; \text{or}\;\; x = $r</mrow>
    </md></li>      
    </case>
  </conditionalContent>
</ul>
</solution>
</problem>


